<paragraph id="8BBF4E2BFFFBFFED9D155ED3FE63C3B3" blockId="33.[264,761,684,745]" box="[264,500,719,745]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFFBFFED9D155ED3FECDC3B3" box="[264,346,719,745]" captionStart="FIGURES 1­10" captionStartId="63.[264,382,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[283,1298,320,1585]" captionTargetId="figure-106@63.[251,1329,299,1605]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 1­10. Right wing of male Ommatius (Pygommatius) spp. 1. O. alatipes, sp. n..; 2. O. albatus Martin; 3. O. bingeri Oldroyd; 4. O. brevicornis Curran; 5. O. cingulatus Bromley; 6. O. comosus, sp. n..; 7. O. dasypogon Oldroyd; 8. O. digittatus Oldroyd; 9. O. fluvius sp. n..; 10. O. grossus, sp. n. Abbr. R4 =fourth radial vein, r4 = fourth radial cell, m1= first medial cell, m3=third medial cell, d = discal cell, r­m = radial­medial crossvein." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019045/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figs. 9</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFFBFFED9D7A5ED3FE10C3B3" box="[359,391,719,745]" captionStart="FIGURES 39­48" captionStartId="67.[264,382,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[272,1308,316,1611]" captionTargetId="figure-101@67.[214,1320,302,1622]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURES 39­48. Left hind tibia of male Ommatius (Pygommatius) spp. 39. O. comosus, sp. n.; 40. O. fluvius, sp. n.; 41. O. imaginus, sp. n.; 42. O. limbus, sp. n., anterior; 43. O. litoreus, sp. n.; 44. O. neglectus Bromley; 45. O. porticus, sp. n.; 46. O. renudus, sp. n.; 47. O. strigiatus, sp. n.; 48. O. vultus, sp. n., inner surface." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019055/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">40</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFFBFFED9D8E5ED3FE63C3B3" box="[403,500,719,745]" captionStart="FIGURES 126­133" captionStartId="78.[264,382,1803,1827]" captionTargetBox="[275,1313,316,1620]" captionTargetId="figure-53@78.[240,1334,308,1646]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURES 126­133. Male terminalia of Ommatius fluvius, sp. n 126­128. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 129. Gonostylus; 130. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female terminalia. 131. Spermatheca; 132. Genital fork; 133. Sternite 8, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019087" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019087/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">126­133</figureCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBF4E2BFFFBFFED9D155F05FDD8C2D9" blockId="33.[264,1323,793,1905]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Male. As 
<taxonomicName id="4C0035A8FFFBFFED9D9E5F05FD87C268" authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Marascia" authorityYear="2003" box="[387,528,793,818]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comosus">
<emphasis id="B9749239FFFBFFED9D9E5F05FD87C268" box="[387,528,793,818]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">O. comosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
except as follows. Length, body 
<quantity id="4CF8E3CEFFFBFFED9FB35F05FB8BC269" box="[942,1052,793,819]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.17" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="11.7">11.7 mm</quantity>
; wing 
<quantity id="4CF8E3CEFFFBFFED986F5F05FB43C269" box="[1138,1236,793,819]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="7.5">7.5 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis id="B9749239FFFBFFED98FE5F05FAB5C268" box="[1251,1314,793,818]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Head</emphasis>
: FHWR 1.0:11.4. Palpus entirely brown. Scape and pedicel brown­yellow dorsally and medially, yellow elsewhere.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBF4E2BFFFBFFED9D255F8DFB52C289" blockId="33.[264,1323,793,1905]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis id="B9749239FFFBFFED9D255F8DFE1BC2F0" box="[312,396,913,938]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Thorax</emphasis>
: Scutellum brown; scattered yellow setae. Pleuron yellow with narrow black triangle extending across anepisternum and katepitergite, triangle widest dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBF4E2BFFFBFFED9D255FFDFB5FC57C" blockId="33.[264,1323,793,1905]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis id="B9749239FFFBFFED9D255FFDFEE3C2A0" box="[312,372,993,1018]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Wing</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFFBFFED9D985FFDFE59C2A1" box="[389,462,993,1019]" captionStart="FIGURES 1­10" captionStartId="63.[264,382,1701,1725]" captionTargetBox="[283,1298,320,1585]" captionTargetId="figure-106@63.[251,1329,299,1605]" captionTargetPageId="63" captionText="FIGURES 1­10. Right wing of male Ommatius (Pygommatius) spp. 1. O. alatipes, sp. n..; 2. O. albatus Martin; 3. O. bingeri Oldroyd; 4. O. brevicornis Curran; 5. O. cingulatus Bromley; 6. O. comosus, sp. n..; 7. O. dasypogon Oldroyd; 8. O. digittatus Oldroyd; 9. O. fluvius sp. n..; 10. O. grossus, sp. n. Abbr. R4 =fourth radial vein, r4 = fourth radial cell, m1= first medial cell, m3=third medial cell, d = discal cell, r­m = radial­medial crossvein." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019045/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
): Narrow apex and posterior margin dense microtrichose. Cell r 
<subScript id="17844C6EFFFBFFED98DD5FF2FB5DC2A5" attach="left" box="[1216,1226,1006,1023]" fontSize="7" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">4</subScript>
with R 
<subScript id="17844C6EFFFBFFED993C5FF2FABCC2A5" attach="right" box="[1313,1323,1006,1023]" fontSize="7" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">5</subScript>
slightly convex medially. Apex of cell m 
<subScript id="17844C6EFFFBFFED9EF85804FD78C573" attach="left" box="[741,751,1048,1065]" fontSize="7" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">3</subScript>
perpendicular to axis of wing, near r­m.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBF4E2BFFFBFFED9D25582BFD02C41B" blockId="33.[264,1323,793,1905]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis id="B9749239FFFBFFED9D25582BFEF3C50A" box="[312,356,1079,1104]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Leg</emphasis>
: Hind trochanter brown­yellow posteriorly and dorsally, yellow anteriorly; 1 short, peg­like bristle present. Fore and middle femora yellow, apex anteriorly and dorsally brown­yellow. Fore femur (see 
<taxonomicName id="4C0035A8FFFBFFED9E65589BFC88C5FA" authorityName=": Hull" authorityYear="1962" box="[632,799,1159,1184]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevicornis">
<emphasis id="B9749239FFFBFFED9E65589BFC88C5FA" box="[632,799,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">O. brevicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFFBFFED9F30589BFC15C5FB" box="[813,898,1159,1185]" captionStart="FIGURES 21­28" captionStartId="65.[264,382,1754,1778]" captionTargetBox="[277,1313,348,1567]" captionTargetId="figure-98@65.[242,1321,324,1693]" captionTargetPageId="65" captionText="FIGURES 21­28. Right wing of male Ommatius (Pygommatius) spp. 21. O. talus, sp. n.; 22. O. vultus, sp. n.; 23­28. Right fore femur of male Ommatius (Pygommatius) spp. showing arrangement of anteroventral bristles. 23. O. brevicornis Curran; 24. O. grossus, sp. n.; 25. O. limbus, sp. n.; 26. O. litoreus, sp. n.; 27. O. strigiatus, sp. n..; 28. O. vultus, sp. n." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019049" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019049/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 23</figureCitation>
) with a ventral row of 7­8 unusually thick, yellow bristles. Middle femur ventrally with only long, thin, yellow setae. Hind femur (see 
<taxonomicName id="4C0035A8FFFBFFED9D8A58CBFDB6C5AA" authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Marascia" authorityYear="2003" box="[407,545,1239,1264]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="comosus">
<emphasis id="B9749239FFFBFFED9D8A58CBFDB6C5AA" box="[407,545,1239,1264]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">O. comosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFFBFFED9E2C58CBFD1FC5AB" box="[561,648,1239,1265]" captionStart="FIGURES 29­38" captionStartId="66.[264,382,1730,1754]" captionTargetId="figure-107@66.[254,1329,297,1495]" captionTargetPageId="66" captionText="FIGURES 29­38. Male Ommatius (Pygommatius) spp. 29. O. jaculator Walker, middle femur. 30­ 38. Hind femur, 30. O. brevicornis Curran, anterior view; 31. O. comosus, sp. n., anterior view; 32. O. dasypogon Oldroyd, anterior view; 33. O. jaculator Walker, anterior view; 34. O. limbus, sp. n., with coxa, anterior view; 35. O. litoreus, sp. n., anterior view; 36. O. neglectus Bromley, anterior view; 37. O. strigiatus, sp. n., posterior view; 38. O. vultus, sp. n., posterior view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5080299" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5080299/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 31</figureCitation>
); HFWLR 1.0:5.7. Hind tibia (
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFFBFFED9FE758CBFBC6C5AB" box="[1018,1105,1239,1265]" captionStart="FIGURES 39­48" captionStartId="67.[264,382,1762,1786]" captionTargetBox="[272,1308,316,1611]" captionTargetId="figure-101@67.[214,1320,302,1622]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="FIGURES 39­48. Left hind tibia of male Ommatius (Pygommatius) spp. 39. O. comosus, sp. n.; 40. O. fluvius, sp. n.; 41. O. imaginus, sp. n.; 42. O. limbus, sp. n., anterior; 43. O. litoreus, sp. n.; 44. O. neglectus Bromley; 45. O. porticus, sp. n.; 46. O. renudus, sp. n.; 47. O. strigiatus, sp. n.; 48. O. vultus, sp. n., inner surface." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019055/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
) slightly calf­like, apex and middle wider than base; anterior, preapical constriction and abundant, erect, brown setae present on basal half.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBF4E2BFFFBFFED9D255953FABCC7DB" blockId="33.[264,1323,793,1905]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis id="B9749239FFFBFFED9D255953FE31C432" box="[312,422,1359,1384]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Mostly brown to yellow brown, with thin brown tomentum and brown setae; wide lateral margins of tergites 1­4 yellow with yellow tomentum with yellow setae; tergite 4 with a thin fringe of 7­8 yellow bristles on apical half of lateral margin; apical margin of tergites 6­8 with apical margin produced medially. Sternites 1­3 yellow, sternite 4 yellowish­brown medially; sternites 4 and 5 with 2 admedial stripes of erect, brown setae, those on sternite 4 short with nearly parallel sides, pencil­like, those on 5 longer with pointed apices; sternite 6 brown setose with 2­3 erect, admedial setae on basal half, setae otherwise shorter and decumbent. Sternite 8 with brown bristles along apical margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBF4E2BFFFBFFED9D255A93FC18C67B" blockId="33.[264,1323,793,1905]" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
<emphasis id="B9749239FFFBFFED9D255A93FE2FC7F2" box="[312,440,1679,1704]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Terminalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFFBFFED9DD65A93FDE0C7F3" box="[459,631,1679,1705]" captionStart="FIGURES 126­133" captionStartId="78.[264,382,1803,1827]" captionTargetBox="[275,1313,316,1620]" captionTargetId="figure-53@78.[240,1334,308,1646]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURES 126­133. Male terminalia of Ommatius fluvius, sp. n 126­128. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 129. Gonostylus; 130. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female terminalia. 131. Spermatheca; 132. Genital fork; 133. Sternite 8, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019087" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019087/files/figure.png" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Figs. 126­130</figureCitation>
): Ventral lamellae with raised median carnia. Epandrium with only 2 obvious branches, dorsal branch wide, dorsal apical corner pointed; ventral branch narrower, slightly longer than dorsal branch, apex asymmertically bifid with stout bristles. Gonocoxite with minute setae in large sockets.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBF4E2BFFFBFFEE9D255B33FE42C264" blockId="33.[264,1323,793,1905]" lastBlockId="34.[264,1323,284,1230]" lastPageId="34" lastPageNumber="35" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Female. Differs from male as follows. Length, body 
<quantity id="4CF8E3CEFFFBFFED9FA85B33FBB4C613" box="[949,1059,1839,1865]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.22" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="12.2">12.2 mm</quantity>
; wing 
<quantity id="4CF8E3CEFFFBFFED986B5B33FB41C613" box="[1142,1238,1839,1865]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" unit="mm" value="9.5">9.5 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis id="B9749239FFFBFFED98FE5B33FAB5C612" box="[1251,1314,1839,1864]" italics="true" pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Head</emphasis>
: Face ventrally with thick brown or yellow bristles; FHWR 1.0:10.6. Pedicel and scape brown. Occiput with brown postocular bristles extending to midlateral margin of eye. 
<emphasis id="B9749239FFF8FFEE98EE5D00FEB8C007" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pleuron with meron partly brown. 
<emphasis id="B9749239FFF8FFEE9EF45D58FC82C007" box="[745,789,324,349]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Leg</emphasis>
: Brown color darker than in male. Unusual vestiture of legs and calf­like shape of hind tibia absent. Fore and middle femora brown on apical third anteriorly and apical half dorsally; middle femur with yellow and brown posteroventral setae. Hind femur brown on apical half, extending dorsally and ventrally to or near base; 2 well defined ventral rows of 4­5 long, thin, brown bristles; abundant, short, bristles present posteriorly; thin ventral and posterior setae absent; HFWLR 1.0:5.7. Fore and middle tibiae with narrow apex brown; all bristles tibiae and tarsi brown. 
<emphasis id="B9749239FFF8FFEE98A95E28FAB4C317" box="[1204,1315,564,589]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Tergites with long, thin brown bristles along apical margin; unusual vestiture of male absent. Tergite 9 about as long as cercus. 
<emphasis id="B9749239FFF8FFEE9EEC5E98FCE6C3C7" box="[753,881,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Terminalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFF8FFEE9F9C5E98FBBDC3C4" box="[897,1066,644,670]" captionStart="FIGURES 126­133" captionStartId="78.[264,382,1803,1827]" captionTargetBox="[275,1313,316,1620]" captionTargetId="figure-53@78.[240,1334,308,1646]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURES 126­133. Male terminalia of Ommatius fluvius, sp. n 126­128. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 129. Gonostylus; 130. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female terminalia. 131. Spermatheca; 132. Genital fork; 133. Sternite 8, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019087" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019087/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Figs. 131­133</figureCitation>
): Three spermathecae present, narrow with sides gradually tapered to apex; duct basal, slightly lateral in position. Apical margin of sternite 8 triangular, sides oblique with a prominent notch laterally; cuticle medially thin with a deep narrow groove extending to apical margin; apical corner with 3­4 thick bristles.
</paragraph>
