</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBF4E2BFFF8FFEE9D255FF0FC80C574" blockId="34.[264,1323,284,1230]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Etymology. Latin 
<taxonomicName id="4C0035A8FFF8FFEE9E0F5FF0FDF7C55F" authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Marascia" authorityYear="2003" box="[530,608,1004,1029]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fluvius">
<emphasis id="B9749239FFF8FFEE9E0F5FF0FDF7C55F" box="[530,608,1004,1029]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">fluvius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, for ‘of or belonging to a stream or river’, referring to the species being found along the Ogoové 
<collectingRegion id="49C480C9FFF8FFEE9ECD5808FC84C574" box="[720,787,1044,1070]" country="Nigeria" name="Rivers" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">River</collectingRegion>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BBF4E2BFFF8FFEE9D255820FBF1C594" blockId="34.[264,1323,284,1230]" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">
Remarks. The male of 
<taxonomicName id="4C0035A8FFF8FFEE9E585820FD20C50F" authorityName="Scarbrough &amp; Marascia" authorityYear="2003" box="[581,695,1084,1109]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Ommatius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="34" pageNumber="35" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fluvius">
<emphasis id="B9749239FFF8FFEE9E585820FD20C50F" box="[581,695,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">O. fluvius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily distinguished from congeners by the unique terminalia (
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFF8FFEE9D925878FDAFC524" box="[399,568,1124,1150]" captionStart="FIGURES 126­133" captionStartId="78.[264,382,1803,1827]" captionTargetBox="[275,1313,316,1620]" captionTargetId="figure-53@78.[240,1334,308,1646]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURES 126­133. Male terminalia of Ommatius fluvius, sp. n 126­128. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 129. Gonostylus; 130. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female terminalia. 131. Spermatheca; 132. Genital fork; 133. Sternite 8, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019087" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019087/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Figs. 126­133</figureCitation>
), the sparse, yellow, fringe of bristles on the lateroapical half of tergite 4, and the sparse, erect, admedial setae on the basal half of sternite 6. The long tergite 8 and deep lateral notch of sternite 8 (
<figureCitation id="133B52AEFFF8FFEE9EF558A8FCDBC594" box="[744,844,1204,1230]" captionStart="FIGURES 126­133" captionStartId="78.[264,382,1803,1827]" captionTargetBox="[275,1313,316,1620]" captionTargetId="figure-53@78.[240,1334,308,1646]" captionTargetPageId="78" captionText="FIGURES 126­133. Male terminalia of Ommatius fluvius, sp. n 126­128. Lateral, dorsal and ventral views; 129. Gonostylus; 130. Aedeagus, lateral view. Female terminalia. 131. Spermatheca; 132. Genital fork; 133. Sternite 8, ventral view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5019087" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5019087/files/figure.png" pageId="34" pageNumber="35">Fig. 133</figureCitation>
) distinguish the female.
</paragraph>
